The paper analyzes the network structure of non-profit foundations in China and their relationship with the state, which falls under the categories of social networks (cs.SOC), cybersecurity (cs.CYBER), and politics (cs.POL). The use of network analysis and cluster analysis suggests a focus on computational social science (cs.SI). Additionally, the paper discusses the role of government officials in non-profit boards, which could also fall under the category of cryptography and security (cs.CR) if there are concerns about potential conflicts of interest or corruption.
